Minor fixes
Fixed output from code sample

Fixed description of how to query

As per the code sample, ```find()``` receives a hash as its first parameter, not the second.

Remove `/connect/` from SMT URL

To configure the installer to use a registration proxy, the FQDN of SMT/RMT is enough. There's no need to append `/connect/`, since the SUSEConnect library takes care of that on its own. In fact, SUSEConnect does not handle paths, and even if `fqdn/connect` is given as the regurl, it will only use `fqdn`, and ignore the path. Giving a path can cause a bug when de-registering a system (bsc#954451).

commit_list.message:
Don't create the license directory if the repo has no license

The `replace_directory(@temp_licenses_dir,...)` call would happen
whether there were licenses downloaded or not. Unfortunately, YaST
checks for the existence of that directorty to see if a product has a
license, but since RMT would create the directory empty, YaST then fails
to read the license file and failed. Now, we only create the license
directory if any licenses were actually downloaded. Solves bsc#1087707.

This commit also ensures that the temp directories created for metadata
and for licenses are always removed. Closes #118.

commit_list.message:
Use the recommended systemd config

Puma specifies a recommended way of starting it with systemd at:
https://github.com/puma/puma/blob/5fb2df9144803f0f80ec1d9fb19d20d433706fef/docs/systemd.md#service-configuration

Type=simple can be used, and then there's not need to --daemon the Rails
server.
Additionally, we set the RAILS_LOG_TO_STDOUT variable, so that Rails
outputs its log to stdout. This allows for the logs to be saved and
visible in journalctl.

The PrivateTmp option "sets up a new file system namespace for the
executed processes and mounts private /tmp and /var/tmp directories
inside it that is not shared by processes outside of the namespace.
(...) all temporary files created by a service in these directories will
be removed after the service is stopped."

Since RMT creates some temporary directories while mirroring, with this
option we isolate them and make sure they get deleted when RMT is
stopped.

Closes #128.

Make Jenkinsfile declarative and better utilize parallelization

Limit on what systems prophet runs

Running on all SLE SPs takes waaay too long. So let's just run on 12SP3
and 15SP0.

Using "successfully run" was not waiting until commands really finished

So it was giving strange errors about "expected (command) to have
finished in time", without giving commands the opportunity to finish. I
could not find a source for this problem, so I just decided to drop it
and go back to "I run". The activate_announcer_on_command_failure option
is only used when using "I successfully run" so it does not make sense
to keep it.

Change startup_wait_time config

Basically, Aruba will `sleep` the amount of time that is configured in
startup_wait_time on EVERY command run, so setting it to a high number
will make tests terribly slow.
But for some reason, we still need to have set it to SOME number in
order for the announcers defined by
activate_announcer_on_command_failure to work. Otherwise, those
announcers show absolutely no output, even though the command did have
SOME output.
I added a new @slow_startup label because the rollback takes a long time
to run and we need to give it some more time.

Properly test connect cli exit codes

`Kernel.exit` was getting stubbed, but our code assumed that after
calling `exit`, no more code would get run. Stubbing `exit` breaks that
expectation, since the code keeps running.
Also, we were not testing the error codes we were throwing in different
scenarios. We are now.

Correctly set the proxy user & pass in Ruby 2.5

Ruby 2.5 changes the way proxies behave from Ruby 2.1.
In Ruby 2.1, Net::HTTP would get the proxy URL from the http_proxy env
var, and then one could set proxy_user and proxy_password directly on
the Net::HTTP object.
In Ruby 2.5, once the proxy URL comes from the http_proxy env var,
setting proxy_user and proxy_password on the Net::HTTP object does
nothing. It assumes that the proxy URL will have the user and password
as part of the URI (eg. http://user:pass@myproxy).
In SLES, the recommended way of setting the proxy user and password is
through the .curlrc file.
Now, what we do is that if we detect that a proxy is being used, we will
re-create the Net::HTTP object, passing all proxy settings to the
initializer.

Use `osc sr` instead of `osc mr`

Strictly speaking, once a product goes into maintenance, you need to
create a "maintenance request" (mr) rather than a "submit request" (sr),
but the `sr` command will automatically transform the request into a
maintenance request. Additionally, `sr` will automatically fill out the
commit message based on the changelog, but `mr` will not, which is
annoying.
